    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 16th prioritizing platoon leverage, headlined by **Yordan Alvarez** (65.44) and **Junior Caminero** (59.77). **Yordan Alvarez** remains our premier start; while the lineup for the Zebras is currently pending, his projected slot in the two-hole against Mejia provides a significant cushion despite a neutral park environment. **Junior Caminero** benefits similarly from his favorable position in the batting order, though his matchup against Leasure requires caution given the pitcher\u2019s respectable 3.44 xERA. We are also deploying **Gary Sanchez** (58.67) as a high-upside UTIL play; his platoon advantage against Corbin is the primary engine driving his score, effectively negating the pitcher's presence to exploit the favorable matchup for power.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved **Josh Smith** (39.60), who narrowly missed the threshold for inclusion. While **Josh Smith** typically benefits from park factors, his negative dynamic platoon split against the left-handed Lopez, combined with a bottom-third batting order projection, dropped him just below our 40.0 floor. We are opting to bench him to preserve game caps, as the efficiency metrics dictate a lean toward high-leverage spots. Elsewhere, the lineup features **Dillon Dingler** (55.99), whose value is bolstered by a strong platoon edge against Bubic. While **Kazuma Okamoto** (52.13) and **Chase Meidroth** (49.85) provide steady, if unremarkable, production, we are monitoring the availability of **Christian Yelich**, who remains on the IL, alongside bench-bound assets like **Pete Crow-Armstrong** and **Kyle Schwarber**, who are unavailable due to off-days. We will continue to track **Trea Turner**, **Caleb Durbin**, **Hyeseong Kim**, **Colt Keith**, **Zac Veen**, **Victor Scott II**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Carson Benge**, and **Luis Pena** as potential rotation pieces for subsequent slates.",
